tensor  invariant
 
is automatically a symmetry of the entire Lagrangian (),
since the latter
is uniquely  determined by the .
These symmetries act as
isometries of the scalar manifold ,
which becomes evident if one rewrites
the kinetic energy term for the scalar fields as 
with the  being constrained according to ().

As there is no interference between these two types of symmetries
(a consequence of the vector and scalar fields being -inert),
 the full global symmetry group
 of ()  factorizes into 
. Obviously, then, any 'unifying' symmetry group has to be a subgroup
of , because only this group acts non-trivially on the vector fields.


For a generic MESGT the invariance group  of the underlying cubic
polynomial  can be rather small or even trivial.
A well-studied class of theories with rather large symmetry groups  are
the ones whose target spaces  are symmetric spaces. This class of
MESGTs can be divided into three families: 


 
