provided by the four magical theories described above.



The goal of the first part of this paper is to find more examples
of unified MESGTs by abandoning the restriction that  be a
symmetric or a homogeneous space(In fact, there is no good
physical motivation for such a restriction.
For one thing, the quantum corrected low energy effective actions of
 compactifications of string  or M-theory are in
general not based on homogeneous target spaces (see e.g. for
some explicit 5D examples).
Moreover, even in an intrinsically 5D  framework, the
deviation from the class of homogeneous target  spaces is often
a crucial step towards obtaining models with interesting physical
properties   (see e.g.   ).) . The
mathematical problem one has to solve in order to find such
theories is easily stated: Find irreducible representations of
simple groups  with an invariant third rank symmetric tensor
 such that the resulting metrics  and
 are positive definite, at least
in
 the vicinity
of some point, , on the hypersurface
. An equivalent way of stating
the positivity properties of  and
 is to require that the 
can be brought to the canonical form () by means of a linear
redefinition of the .

In the following section, we show that an infinite number of solutions to this
mathematical problem can be easily constructed using
the language of Jordan algebras.










Jordan algebras and unified MESGTs 
As we have seen in the previous section, within the class of
symmetric or homogeneous scalar manifolds only four give rise to a
unified MESGT. These four theories are all members of what we
called the "magical Jordan family" (family (ii)). The magical
Jordan family and the generic Jordan family (family (i)) owe their
names to the fact that they are associated with Jordan algebras.
The "symmetric non-Jordan family" (family (iii)), by contrast,
is, as the name suggests,  not connected to Jordan algebras. In
order to become more explicit, let us first recall the definition
of a Jordan algebra.



Definition 1: 
 A Jordan algebra over a field  (which we take to be 
 or
) is an an algebra, , over  
with a symmetric product ,
 
that satisfies
the Jordan identity
 
where .



The Jordan identity () is automatically satisfied when
the product  is associative, but
() does not imply associativity. In other words, a
Jordan algebra is  in general not associative.
Historically, Jordan algebras were introduced in an attempt to
generalize the formalism of quantum mechanics by
capturing the algebraic essence of Hermitian operators corresponding
to observables without reference to the
underlying Hilbert space on which they act. While the
Hermitian    operators acting on a Hilbert
space do not close under the ordinary (associative) operator product,
they do close and form a Jordan algebra
under the Jordan product  defined as one half the
anticommutator (The axioms () and
() are of course also fulfilled for other multiples of the
anticommutator. The prefactor one half
is singled out as the only prefactor for which eq. ()
becomes independent of the degree  of the
Jordan algebra.) .


For every Jordan algebra , one can define a norm
form, , that satisfies the
composition property 
The degree, , of the norm form is defined by ,
where .  is also called
 the degree of the Jordan algebra.



Definition 2: 
A Euclidean  Jordan algebra is a Jordan algebra for which
the condition  implies that  for all
. The automorphism groups of Euclidean Jordan algebras
are always compact.



