  and  would not all be negative.
Hence, only the Minkowskian signatures can lead to physically
acceptable unified MESGTs.




Putting everything together, we have thus shown the following:
If one identifies the -symbols () of the traceless elements
of a Minkowskian Jordan algebra  with the
 of a MESGT: ,
one obtains a unified MESGT, in which all the vector fields transform
irreducibly under the simple automorphism group
 of that Jordan algebra.

For  one obtains in
this way three infinite families of physically
acceptable unified MESGTs (one for each ). For the
octonionic case, the situation is a bit different. The
-symbols of the octonionic Minkowskian Hermitian 
-matrices with the anticommutator product
all lead to positive definite metrics  and
, i.e., to physically
acceptable MESGTs. For , however, these octonionic
Hermitian matrix algebras are no longer Jordan
algebras.
 Surprisingly, the automorphism groups of these octonionic  algebras
  for  do not have the automorphism group
  of  as a subgroup.
Instead, the  automorphism groups for 
 are direct product groups of the form  .  None
of these two factors acts irreducibly on all the traceless elements, and hence
  the corresponding  MESGTs are  not unified
 theories. Thus, the  MESGT defined by the exceptional Minkowskian
Jordan algebra  is the only unified 
MESGT of this infinite tower of otherwise acceptable octonionic theories.







