Unified   Yang-Mills-Einstein    supergravity theories 





In the previous section, we have constructed infinitely many
novel unified   MESGTs in five dimensions by establishing a
relation to a
certain class of non-compact Jordan algebras.
As we did not give a completeness proof, it   is not clear
whether these novel theories
(together with the remaining magical one based on the compact Jordan
algebra  found in)
exhaust all possible unified MESGTs in five dimensions.
In order to answer that question, one would have to show that there are
no further irreducible representations of simple groups with an invariant
symmetric tensor of rank three that gives rise to positive metrics
 and
. We leave this as an open problem.


Instead, we will now, in this section,
try to construct novel  unified Yang-Mills -Einstein
supergravity theories, i.e., theories in which
 all the vector fields, including the graviphoton, transform irreducibly
in the adjoint representation of a simple local  gauge group, .
If one turns off the gauge coupling of such a unified YMESGT, the local
symmetry group  becomes a global symmetry group under which the vector
fields still transform irreducibly. In other words, turning off the
gauge coupling of a unified YMESGT yields a unified MESGT.
Conversely, any unified YMESGT
can be obtained from a unified MESGT, by gauging a suitable subgroup
 of the global symmetry group  of the MESGT.



Let us briefly review some of the technical aspects of such
a gauging. In the unified MESGT one starts with,
the  vector
fields  form an irreducible -dimensional
representation
of the simple global symmetry group . If one wants to construct
a unified YMESGT out of this unified MESGT,
one has to gauge an -dimensional
simple subgroup  of . For this to be
possible, the -dimensional
